'''Christopher Grant Wood''' (born 7 December 1991) is a New Zealand professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]] for {{English football updater|NottingF}} club [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] and [[Captain (association football)|captains]] the [[New Zealand men's national football team|New Zealand national team]]. Widely regarded as one of New Zealand's greatest ever footballers,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newsroom.co.nz/2025/02/07/chris-wood-could-be-nzs-best-footballer-ever/|title=Chris Wood could be NZ's best footballer, ever|first=Alexia|last=Russell|date=6 February 2025}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/news/sport/533637/is-chris-wood-nz-football-s-greatest-of-all-time|title=Is Chris Wood NZ football's greatest of all time?|first1=Mathew|last1=Nash|first2=Local Democracy|last2=Reporting|date=13 November 2024|website=RNZ}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.colossusbets.com/blog/the-best-new-zealand-players-in-premier-league-history/|title=The best New Zealand players in Premier League history|first=Andrew|last=Roach|date=8 May 2022}}</ref> Wood is one of just six New Zealanders to have played in the Premier League.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/football/english-premier-league/the-six-kiwis-to-have-played-in-the-premier-league/EZOL7MZBK772G7K7MCG2TEMH4A/|title=The six Kiwis to have played in the EPL|date=21 August 2017|website=NZ Herald}}</ref>

Wood started his senior career with [[Cambridge FC|Cambridge]], [[WaiBOP United|Waikato]] and [[Hamilton Wanderers AFC|Hamilton Wanderers]] before moving to England to play for Premier League club [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]]. He spent his time on loan at six clubs before joining [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]] in 2013. After a loan spell with [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]] in 2015, he signed for [[EFL Championship|Championship]] club [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]], where he became the top scorer in the [[2016–17 EFL Championship|2016–17 season]], with 27 goals. Wood then joined [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] for a club record fee, and became a consistent goalscorer for them in the Premier League, notching up 49 goals in 144 matches over four and a half seasons. In January 2022, he joined [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] for [[Pound sterling|£]]25&nbsp;million (€29&nbsp;million), making him the [[List of most expensive association football transfers|most expensive Oceania player of all time]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Newcastle transfer news: Chris Wood signs from Burnley in £25m deal to become second January arrival |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11678/12514215/newcastle-transfer-news-chris-wood-signs-from-burnley-in-25m-deal-to-become-second-january-arrival |date=13 January 2022 |access-date=13 May 2024 |website=Sky Sports}}</ref>

After joining Nottingham Forest in 2023, Wood went on to become the club's all-time leading Premier League goalscorer, surpassing [[Bryan Roy]]'s long-standing record of 24 goals.<ref name="forest_record">{{cite news |title=Chris Wood becomes Forest's all-time leading Premier League scorer |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/cd64gq5lvpxo |work=BBC Sport |date=20 January 2025 |access-date=3 October 2025}}</ref> During the [[2024–25 Premier League]] season, Wood equalled his career-best goal tally by mid-January, having scored 14 goals in 22 matches.<ref name="form">{{cite news |title=Chris Wood matches his all-time best Premier League goal tally |url=https://www.friendsoffootballnz.com/2025/01/20/watch-all-whites-chris-wood-scores-again-to-match-his-all-time-best-season/ |work=Friends of Football NZ |date=20 January 2025 |access-date=3 October 2025}}</ref> He later went on to finish the campaign with 20 Premier League goals, the first time he had reached that milestone in a single season.<ref name="20goals">{{cite news |title=Chris Wood reaches 20 Premier League goals for the season |url=https://www.friendsoffootballnz.com/2025/05/12/watch-diving-header-gives-all-whites-chris-wood-20th-his-goal-of-the-season/ |work=Friends of Football NZ |date=12 May 2025 |access-date=3 October 2025}}</ref>

Wood earned 90 caps for the [[New Zealand men's national football team|New Zealand national team]], making him the country's most-capped player, while his record 45 international goals also make him their all-time leading goalscorer. He ranks second among all New Zealand internationals, male or female, for international goals, behind only [[Amber Hearn]]. Wood represented New Zealand at the [[2010 FIFA World Cup]] and was a member of the squad that won the [[2016 OFC Nations Cup]].

==Early and personal life==
Wood was born in [[Auckland]]<ref name=Hugman1011/> to Grant and Julie Wood; his mother is from England.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Easby |first=Josh |date=27 October 2017 |title=The Making Of A star: How Chris Wood become New Zealand football's hot property |url=https://issuu.com/hurricanepress/docs/fanz_8 |magazine=FANZ: The Football Magazine |location=New Zealand |access-date=2 January 2022 |archive-date=1 March 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230301014757/https://issuu.com/hurricanepress/docs/fanz_8 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Wood began his footballing career at [[Onehunga Sports]]; after moving to [[Hamilton, New Zealand|Hamilton]] aged 11, he attended [[St Paul's Collegiate School]].

Wood's sister, Chelsey Wood, is also a footballer, and has represented New Zealand at under-20 level.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.oceaniafootball.com/ofc/News/ViewArticle/tabid/125/Article/7315b96e-389a-4b78-86b5-96d74d1ad4bb/Default.aspx |title=Junior Football Ferns named for cup |publisher=Oceania Football Confederation |date=29 June 2010 |access-date=19 November 2015 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151119235509/http://www.oceaniafootball.com/ofc/News/ViewArticle/tabid/125/Article/7315b96e-389a-4b78-86b5-96d74d1ad4bb/Default.aspx |archive-date=19 November 2015}}</ref>

In June 2024, Wood married his long-term partner Emma Lovell, a solicitor.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/350316308/all-whites-star-chris-wood-marries-luxurious-italian-hotel |title=All Whites star Chris Wood marries at luxurious Italian hotel |website=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]] |date=19 June 2024 |access-date=16 August 2024}}</ref> In October 2024, Wood revealed that he and his wife are expecting a baby girl, Wood's first child.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.1news.co.nz/2024/10/22/its-childs-play-as-chris-wood-scores-winner-for-forest/ |title=It's child's play as Chris Wood scores winner for Forest |website=[[1News]] |date=22 October 2024 |access-date=1 November 2024}}</ref>

==Club career==
===Early career===
Wood began his senior career with [[Cambridge FC|Cambridge]], scoring on his debut in the [[Lotto Sport Italia NRFL Division 2|NRFL Division 2]] in 2006 aged just 14, and after a spell at local rivals [[Hamilton Wanderers AFC|Hamilton Wanderers]] the following season in the [[Northern League (New Zealand)|NRFL Premier]],<ref name="Hamilton">{{cite news|url=https://www.friendsoffootballnz.com/2024/11/12/feature-the-best-all-whites-goalscorer-from-the-waikato-youve-never-heard-of/#:~:text=Wood%20scored%20an%20impressive%2016,rose%20to%20football%20prominence%2C%20so|title=Feature: The best All Whites goalscorer from the Waikato you've never heard of|access-date=17 November 2024 |website=Friends of football |date=12 November 2024 |archive-date=25 April 2025 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250425171152/https://www.friendsoffootballnz.com/2024/11/12/feature-the-best-all-whites-goalscorer-from-the-waikato-youve-never-heard-of/ |url-status=live }}</ref> he attracted the attention of [[New Zealand Football Championship|ASB Premiership]] club [[WaiBOP United|Waikato]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/waikato-times/sport/2331366/City-teen-plays-his-way-into-big-time |title=City teen plays his way into big time |first=Matt |last=Richens |newspaper=[[Waikato Times]] |location=Hamilton |date=13 April 2009 |access-date=26 August 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cambridgefootball.co.nz/2018/02/02/the-making-of-an-all-white-the-chris-wood-story/ |title=The making of an All White: The Chris Wood story |date=2 February 2018 |access-date=31 March 2018 |archive-date=17 September 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210917164803/http://www.cambridgefootball.co.nz/2018/02/02/the-making-of-an-all-white-the-chris-wood-story/ |url-status=dead }}</ref>

===West Bromwich Albion===
Wood was recommended to [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]]'s Academy by coach Roger Wilkinson, who set up a trial for him.<ref name=birminghammail>{{cite news |url=http://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/west-broms-kiwi-star-chris-90590 |title=West Brom's Kiwi star Chris Wood is keeping his feet on the ground |first=Chris |last=Lepkowski |newspaper=Birmingham Mail |date=18 April 2009 |access-date=31 October 2013}}</ref> He found a rich vein of goal scoring form for West Brom's youth academy side, leading to a call-up to the reserve team where he was just as prolific.<ref name=NZ5>{{cite web |url=http://www.hitc.com/en-gb/2017/04/19/west-brom-will-regret-letting-leeds-uniteds-15m-rated-chris-w/ |title=West Brom surely regret letting Leeds United's £15m-rated Chris Wood go |date=19 April 2017 |website=HITC |publisher=GRV Media |last=Owen |first=Danny |access-date=11 March 2018 |archive-date=11 March 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180311202812/http://www.hitc.com/en-gb/2017/04/19/west-brom-will-regret-letting-leeds-uniteds-15m-rated-chris-w/ |url-status=dead }}</ref> Injuries to several West Brom players saw Wood handed a surprise call up to the first-team for a Premier League match against [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]] at [[Fratton Park]] in April 2009. He came on as a [[Substitute (association football)|substitute]] to become just the fifth New Zealander to play in the Premier League.<ref name="NZ5"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wba.co.uk/page/MatchReport/0,,10366~45060,00.html |title=Portsmouth vs WBA |publisher=West Bromwich Albion F.C. |date=11 April 2009 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090414055911/http://www.wba.co.uk/page/MatchReport/0%2C%2C10366~45060%2C00.html |archive-date=14 April 2009}}</ref>

At the end of the [[2008–09 in English football|2008–09 season]], Wood signed his first professional contract, of two years with a further two-year option in the club's favour.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wba.co.uk/page/News/0,,10366~1667472,00.html |title=Wood pens pro contract |publisher=West Bromwich Albion F.C. |date=29 May 2009 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120229164656/http://www.wba.co.uk/page/News/0%2C%2C10366~1667472%2C00.html |archive-date=29 February 2012}}</ref> This was followed in December 2009 with a new three-and-a-half-year deal, with West Brom having the option to extend that for a further year.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wba.co.uk/page/ProfilesDetail/0,,10366~46979,00.html |title=Profiles: Chris Wood |publisher=West Bromwich Albion F.C. |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100611050025/http://www.wba.co.uk/page/ProfilesDetail/0%2C%2C10366~46979%2C00.html |archive-date=11 June 2010}}</ref> He scored his first professional goal for West Brom on 15 September 2009, a "stunning" 25-yard strike into the top left corner, in a 3–1 win over [[Doncaster Rovers F.C.|Doncaster Rovers]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_div_1/8244611.stm |title=West Brom 3–1 Doncaster |website=BBC Sport |date=15 September 2009 |access-date=31 October 2013}}</ref>

====Loan spells====
Wood was sent out on a 93-day emergency [[Loan (association football)|loan]] to [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]] on 24 September 2010.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/9027127.stm |title=Baggies loan teenage striker Chris Wood to Barnsley |website=BBC Sport |date=24 September 2010 |access-date=31 October 2010}}</ref> The loan was terminated early by mutual consent after seven league appearances for the club without scoring.<ref name="seagulls"/>

[[File:ChrisWood.JPG|thumb|upright|Wood playing for [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]] in 2011]]

On 19 November, Wood signed for [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]] on loan until January 2011.<ref name=seagulls>{{cite news |url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/9210452.stm |title=West Brom striker Chris Wood signs for Brighton on loan |website=BBC Sport |date=19 November 2010 |access-date=31 October 2013}}</ref> He scored on his debut against [[Bristol Rovers F.C.|Bristol Rovers]] but saw a [[penalty kick (association football)|penalty]] saved just days later against [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.theargus.co.uk/sport/15165457.The_former__boy_in_a_man_s_body__is_at_the_top_of_his_game_and_ready_to_sink_Albion/ |title=How Chris Wood grew from the "boy in a man's body" to a star striker lining up trouble for Brighton and Hove Albion |first=Brian |last=Owen |newspaper=The Argus |location=Brighton |date=18 March 2017 |access-date=19 February 2018}}</ref><ref name="sb1011"/> He added to his scoring tally in the 3–1 FA Cup win over Portsmouth,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2011/jan/08/brighton-hove-albion-portsmouth-fa-cup |title=Impressive Brighton send Portsmouth crashing out of the FA Cup |first=John |last=Ashdown |newspaper=The Observer |location=London |date=8 January 2011 |access-date=19 February 2018}}</ref> and scored twice against [[Peterborough United F.C.|Peterborough United]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_div_2/9359261.stm |title=Brighton 3–1 Peterborough |website=BBC Sport |date=15 January 2011 |access-date=19 February 2018}}</ref>

The day before the first match of the [[EFL Championship|Championship]] season, Wood joined [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] on a one-month loan.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/14420327 |title=Birmingham City sign West Brom striker Chris Wood |website=BBC Sport |date=5 August 2011 |access-date=31 October 2013}}</ref> He made his debut the following day, replacing [[Keith Fahey]] in the second half of a 2–1 defeat at [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/14352007 |title=Derby 2–1 Birmingham |website=BBC Sport |date=6 August 2011 |access-date=7 August 2011}}</ref> Playing as the lone striker in Birmingham's first match in major European competition for nearly 50 years, the [[2011–12 UEFA Europa League#Play-off round|Europa League play-off round]] first leg against Portuguese club [[C.D. Nacional|Nacional]], Wood hit the frame of the goal twice. The game finished goalless.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/nacional-0-birmingham-city-0-159852 |title=Nacional 0, Birmingham City 0 |first=Colin |last=Tattum |newspaper=Birmingham Mail |date=19 August 2011 |access-date=31 October 2013}}</ref> He scored his first goal for Birmingham in the second leg of the tie against Nacional.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/14569506 |title=Birmingham 3–0 Nacional (agg 3–0) |website=BBC Sport |date=25 August 2011 |access-date=26 August 2011}}</ref> On 11 September, Wood scored a [[Hat-trick (association football)|hat-trick]] to lead Birmingham to victory over [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.skysports.com/football/birmham-vs-millwall/244969 |title=Wood hat-trick tames Lions |website=Sky Sports |date=11 September 2011 |access-date=19 November 2015}}</ref> followed by two goals against [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] on 2 October to take his league total to seven goals from eight games.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/15051285 |title=Nott'm Forest 1–3 Birmingham |website=BBC Sport |date=2 October 2011 |access-date=2 October 2011}}</ref> His loan was then extended for a second time, until 5 January 2012.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/15191122 |title=Birmingham extend loan of West Brom's Chris Wood until January |website=BBC Sport |date=5 October 2011 |access-date=31 October 2013}}</ref> His eighth, to clinch a 2–0 win over [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]], came when [[Marlon King]] played a cross-field ball for Wood to run on to and, according to ''[[The Independent]]'', "the composure he revealed to go past [[Kasper Schmeichel]] and slot the ball home from an angle was impressive".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/football-league/eriksson-refuses-to-see-red-as-leicester-pay-for-indiscipline-2371649.html |title=Eriksson refuses to see red as Leicester pay for indiscipline |newspaper=The Independent |location=London |first=Jon |last=Culley |date=17 October 2011 |access-date=17 October 2011}}</ref> Four days later, Wood scored in the 10th minute of stoppage time to defeat [[Club Brugge K.V.|Club Brugge]] 2–1 in the [[2011–12 UEFA Europa League group stage|Europa League group stage]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/match/2007339--club-brugge-vs-birmingham/ |title=Birmingham strike late to beat Club Brugge |publisher=UEFA |date=20 October 2011 |access-date=22 October 2011}}</ref> His loan ended on 5 January 2012, after 29 games in all competitions from which he scored 11 goals.<ref name="sb1112"/>

After returning to West Bromwich Albion as an unused substitute in their third round FA Cup tie against [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wba.co.uk/page/MatchReport/0,,10366~61412,00.html |title=WBA vs Cardiff City |publisher=West Bromwich Albion F.C. |date=7 January 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120518082331/http://www.wba.co.uk/page/MatchReport/0%2C%2C10366~61412%2C00.html |archive-date=18 May 2012}}</ref> Wood joined Championship club [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]] on loan until the end of the 2011–12 season.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/16528662 |title=West Brom forward Chris Wood joins Bristol City on loan |website=BBC Sport |date=12 January 2012 |access-date=12 January 2012}}</ref> He scored three goals during his loan spell with the club, his first goal coming on his home debut in a 2–1 win over Doncaster Rovers on 21 January.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bristol City 2–1 Doncaster |work=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/16559163 |access-date=10 March 2018}}</ref> His other two goals came in back to back matches, one against Nottingham Forest on 7 April, where it was the only goal of the game,<ref>{{cite web |title=Nott'm Forest 0–1 Bristol City |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/17570898 |website=BBC Sport |date=7 April 2012|access-date=10 March 2018}}</ref> and then two days later at home to [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]] in a 3–1 win.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bristol City 3–1 Coventry |work=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/17581337 |access-date=10 March 2018}}</ref>

On 17 September 2012, Wood completed a two-month loan deal to Championship side Millwall.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11698/8086593/millwall-seal-wood-loan-deal |title=Millwall seal Wood loan deal |website=Sky Sports |date=17 September 2012 |access-date=19 February 2018}}</ref> He made his Millwall debut as a substitute for [[Darius Henderson]] against Cardiff City, and on his first start, scored a consolation goal against his former club Brighton & Hove Albion.<ref name="sb1213"/> On 18 November, Wood extended his loan until January 2013, and scored the winner against [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]] on the same day.<ref>{{cite news |title=Millwall 1–0 Leeds |work=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/20286134 |access-date=26 February 2018}}</ref> On 24 November, he scored the opening goal away to [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]], a powerful shot from 25 yards, helping the visitors to a 2–0 victory.<ref>{{cite web |title=Millwall up to sixth in the Championship after 2–0 win at Blackburn Rovers |url=http://www.skysports.com/football/blackburn-vs-millwall/262286 |website=Sky Sports |date=25 November 2012|access-date=26 February 2018}}</ref>

===Leicester City===
[[File:Chris Wood Training.jpg|thumb|upright|Wood warming up for [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]] in 2013]]
West Bromwich Albion recalled Wood from Millwall on 27 December 2012, and announced the following day that they had accepted offers from Millwall and fellow Championship club Leicester City for the permanent transfer of Wood. He chose to join the latter, and the move was expected to be completed when the January 2013 transfer window opens.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wba.co.uk/news/2012/december/wood-set-to-join-foxes/ |title=Wood set to join Foxes |publisher=West Bromwich Albion F.C. |date=28 December 2012 |access-date=28 December 2012}}</ref> Leicester confirmed that the player had agreed personal terms.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.lcfc.com/news/434369 |title=Terms agreed for Wood |publisher=Leicester City F.C. |date=28 December 2012 |access-date=19 February 2018}}</ref> Wood started and scored twice after only 24 minutes in his first game for Leicester on 1 January 2013 against Huddersfield Town, initially joining on loan to be registered in time to play.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thisisleicestershire.co.uk/New-striker-Chris-Wood-perfect-tonic-Leicester/story-17738915-detail/story.html |title=New striker Chris Wood is perfect tonic for Leicester City's promotion push |newspaper=Leicester Mercury |date=2 January 2013 |access-date=10 January 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130104195554/http://www.thisisleicestershire.co.uk/New-striker-Chris-Wood-perfect-tonic-Leicester/story-17738915-detail/story.html |archive-date=4 January 2013}}</ref>

On 12 January 2013, Wood scored a first-half hat-trick against Bristol City at [[Ashton Gate Stadium|Ashton Gate]] to take his goal tally to six goals in three games for Leicester. He finished the regular season with 11 goals in 24 appearances, helping Leicester qualify for the Championship play-offs. On 12 May 2013, Wood played in the semi-final second leg against [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] but the team were knocked out by the opposition 3–2 on aggregate.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/competitions/championship/10052075/Watford-3-Leicester-City-1-agg-3-2-match-report.html |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220112/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/competitions/championship/10052075/Watford-3-Leicester-City-1-agg-3-2-match-report.html |archive-date=12 January 2022 |url-access=subscription |url-status=live |title=Watford 3 Leicester City 1 (agg 3–2): match report |first=Tom |last=Prentki |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |date=12 May 2013 |access-date=2 September 2014}}{{cbignore}}</ref>

On 26 March 2014, TV footage appeared to support Leicester goalkeeper Kasper Schmeichel's claim that he had scored what would have been the first goal of his career, when Leicester equalised in injury time against [[Yeovil Town F.C.|Yeovil Town]]. However, the match officials ruled that his header had not crossed the line, and the goal was officially credited to Wood, who followed up to put the ball in the net.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://en.espn.co.uk/football/sport/story/294725.html |title=Spoilsports! League deny Schmeichel goal |publisher=ESPN |date=26 March 2014 |access-date=19 November 2015}}</ref> Five days later, after replacing [[Jamie Vardy]] as a substitute, Wood scored a "stunning" long-range volley against [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] to put Leicester six points clear at the top of the Championship.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/Leicester-City-Goal-hero-Chris-Wood-set-play-key/story-20882751-detail/story.html |title=Leicester City: Goal hero Chris Wood is all set to play a key role |newspaper=Leicester Mercury |date=31 March 2014 |access-date=31 March 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140402234746/http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/Leicester-City-Goal-hero-Chris-Wood-set-play-key/story-20882751-detail/story.html |archive-date=2 April 2014}}</ref> Wood finished the season with 8 goals in all competitions as Leicester were promoted to the Premier League at the end of the season as champions.<ref name="sb1314"/>

On 16 August 2014, he came on for [[Leonardo Ulloa]] after 78 minutes of Leicester's first match of the Premier League season, at home to [[Everton F.C.|Everton]]. Seven minutes later he scored the equaliser in a 2–2 draw.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/28718336 |title=Leicester 2–2 Everton |first=Luke |last=Reddy |website=BBC Sport |date=16 August 2014 |access-date=19 February 2018}}</ref>

On 27 February 2015, Wood joined [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]] on loan until the end of the season.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/31659981 |title=Chris Wood: Leicester City striker joins Ipswich on loan |website=BBC Sport |date=27 February 2015 |access-date=14 February 2018}}</ref> He made his debut for Ipswich against [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]] on 1 March,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cartwright |first1=Phil |title=Norwich City 2–0 Ipswich |work=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/31572580 |access-date=26 February 2018}}</ref> playing eight matches for them without scoring. However, on 25 April, he was recalled by his parent club during their successful fight to avoid relegation from the Premier League.<ref>{{cite web |title=Wood Returns to Leicester |url=https://www.itfc.co.uk/news/2015/april/wood-returns-to-leicester-/ |publisher=Ipswich Town F.C. |access-date=26 February 2018}}</ref>

===Leeds United===
On 1 July 2015, Wood joined Championship club Leeds United on a four-year contract for an undisclosed fee,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.leedsunited.com/news/team-news/1166/wood-completes-united-switch |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180219210816/https://www.leedsunited.com/news/team-news/1166/wood-completes-united-switch |url-status=dead |archive-date=19 February 2018 |title=Wood completes United switch |publisher=Leeds United F.C. |date=1 July 2015 |access-date=19 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/33343733 |title=Chris Wood: Leeds United sign Leicester City striker |website=BBC Sport |date=1 July 2015 |access-date=1 July 2015}}</ref> reported to be in the range of {{nowrap|£2.5–3 million}}.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/Leicester-City-confirm-sale-Chris-Wood-Leeds/story-26811812-detail/story.html |title=Leicester City confirm sale of Chris Wood to Leeds United |newspaper=Leicester Mercury |date=1 July 2015 |access-date=1 July 2015 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150802023151/http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/Leicester-City-confirm-sale-Chris-Wood-Leeds/story-26811812-detail/story.html |archive-date=2 August 2015}}<br />{{cite news |url=http://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/leeds-united/latest-whites-news/leeds-united-sign-3m-leicester-city-striker-chris-wood-1-7332801 |title=Leeds United sign £3m Leicester City striker Chris Wood |first=Leon |last=Wobschall |newspaper=Yorkshire Evening Post |location=Leeds |date=1 July 2015 |access-date=1 July 2015}}</ref> As a result, he became Leeds' most expensive signing since the arrival of [[Nick Barmby]] in August 2002.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/football/leeds-united/leeds-united-payback-promise-from-new-boy-wood-1-7337326 |title=Leeds United: Payback promise from new boy Wood |first=Leon |last=Wobschall |newspaper=Yorkshire Evening Post |location=Leeds |date=2 July 2015 |access-date=14 February 2018}}<br />{{cite news |url=https://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/football/leeds-united/leeds-united-big-money-deal-for-wood-takes-rosler-by-surprise-1-7337597 |title=Leeds United: Big-money deal for Wood takes Rosler by surprise |newspaper=Yorkshire Evening Post |location=Leeds |date=2 July 2015 |access-date=2 July 2015}}</ref> Wood was given the number 9 shirt for the coming season.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.leedsunited.com/news/team-news/1058/2015-16-squad-numbers-announced |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180219210813/https://www.leedsunited.com/news/team-news/1058/2015-16-squad-numbers-announced |url-status=dead |archive-date=19 February 2018 |title=2015/16 squad numbers announced |publisher=Leeds United F.C. |date=31 July 2015 |access-date=19 February 2018}}</ref> On 8 August, the opening day of the season, Wood made his debut for Leeds in the Championship in a 1–1 draw against Burnley.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.leedsunited.com/news/team-news/1023/united-in-opening-day-draw |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170912192013/https://www.leedsunited.com/news/team-news/1023/united-in-opening-day-draw |url-status=dead |archive-date=12 September 2017 |title=United in opening day draw |publisher=Leeds United F.C. |date=8 August 2015 |access-date=19 February 2018}}</ref> Four days later, Wood missed his attempt in a [[penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalty shoot-out]] against Doncaster Rovers in the League Cup, with Leeds losing the shoot-out 4–2 after a 1–1 draw.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.leedsunited.com/news/team-news/1002/doncaster-united-exit-cup-on-penalties |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170912192555/https://www.leedsunited.com/news/team-news/1002/doncaster-united-exit-cup-on-penalties |url-status=dead |archive-date=12 September 2017 |title=Doncaster: United exit Cup on penalties |publisher=Leeds United F.C. |date=12 August 2015 |access-date=19 February 2018}}</ref> Wood scored his first goal for Leeds on 19 August in a 2–2 draw with Bristol City. Near the end of the season, he scored his 13th goal of the season on 7 May 2016 against [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston North End]] in a 1–1 draw to finish as his club's top goal scorer for the 2015–16 season.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.leedsunited.com/news/team-news/64/report-spoils-shared-at-preston |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170730014322/https://www.leedsunited.com/news/team-news/64/report-spoils-shared-at-preston |url-status=dead |archive-date=30 July 2017 |title=Report: spoils shared at Preston |publisher=Leeds United F.C. |date=7 May 2016 |access-date=19 February 2018}}</ref>

[[File:Chris wood Leeds 2016.jpg|thumb|upright|Wood playing for [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]] in 2016]]

Wood scored his first goal of the following season on 10 August 2016, in their League Cup fixture against [[Fleetwood Town F.C.|Fleetwood Town]],<ref name="sb1617"/> and his first league goal was an injury-time equaliser a week later with a [[bicycle kick]] in a 1–1 draw with Fulham.<ref name="sb1617"/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.skysports.com/football/leeds-vs-fulham/358140 |title=Leeds 1–1 Fulham: Late Chris Wood strike earns point for home side |agency=PA Sport |website=Sky Sports |date=16 August 2016 |access-date=24 May 2017}}</ref> He scored again in the next match, as Leeds beat [[Sheffield Wednesday]] 2–0, and by the end of September had seven goals in all competitions.<ref name=sb1617/> His ninth goal of the season came in extra time of the League Cup fourth-round tie against Norwich to make the score 2–2, and he converted his kick as Leeds won in a penalty shoot-out.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/sport/football/leeds-united/league-cup-resilient-leeds-united-defy-odds-to-win-shoot-out-and-reach-last-eight-1-8200542 |title=League Cup: Resilient Leeds United defy odds to win shoot-out and reach last eight |first=Lee |last=Sobot |newspaper=The Yorkshire Post |location=Leeds |date=25 October 2016 |access-date=24 May 2017}}</ref><ref name=sb1617/> He opened the scoring against [[Reading F.C.|Reading]] in mid-December, but had to leave the field in the first half with what proved to be a minor hamstring injury.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/football/leeds-united/leeds-united-2-reading-0-chris-wood-injury-worry-for-whites-boss-monk-1-8288424 |title=Leeds United 2 Reading 0: Chris Wood injury worry for Whites boss Monk |first=Phil |last=Hay |newspaper=Yorkshire Evening Post |location=Leeds |date=13 December 2016 |access-date=24 May 2017}}<br />{{cite news |url=http://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/football/leeds-united/leeds-united-key-trio-back-in-contention-to-face-preston-1-8304595 |title=Leeds United: Key trio back in contention to face Preston |first=Lee |last=Sobot |newspaper=Yorkshire Evening Post |location=Leeds |date=23 December 2016 |access-date=24 May 2017}}</ref>

Wood's 16th goal of the season, in a 1–0 win against Derby County on 13 January, sent Leeds third in the Championship table.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2017/jan/13/leeds-united-derby-county-championship-match-report |title=Chris Wood heads Leeds up to third with win over Derby County |agency=Press Association |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |location=London |date=13 January 2017 |access-date=24 May 2017}}</ref> A week later, he scored twice in a 3–2 defeat against Barnsley; this was the first time that Leeds had lost a match in which Wood had scored.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/football/leeds-united/barnsley-3-leeds-united-2-yep-jury-verdicts-on-whites-oakwell-defeat-1-8347566 |title=Barnsley 3 Leeds United 2: YEP jury verdicts on Whites' Oakwell defeat |first=Gary |last=Newbould |newspaper=Yorkshire Evening Post |location=Leeds |date=23 January 2017 |access-date=24 May 2017}}</ref> He reached 20 for the season on 25 January in a 2–0 win over Nottingham Forest that returned Leeds to third in the table,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-soccer-england-championship/wood-grabs-20th-goal-as-leeds-down-forest-2-0-idUKKBN1592SM |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171022085622/https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-soccer-england-championship/wood-grabs-20th-goal-as-leeds-down-forest-2-0-idUKKBN1592SM |url-status=dead |archive-date=22 October 2017 |title=Wood grabs 20th goal as Leeds down Forest 2–0 |work=Reuters |date=25 January 2017 |access-date=19 February 2018}}</ref> and continued to score regularly,<ref name="sb1617"/> although Leeds were unable to maintain their playoff position. His last goal of the season, a penalty to equalise in a 1–1 draw with [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]], took him to 30 goals in all competitions, and his 27 in the league made him the Championship top scorer.<ref name="Press1617">{{cite news |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/the-press/sport/football/92326781/Chris-Wood-scores-in-final-game-of-Leeds-Uniteds-season-to-secure-golden-boot |title=Chris Wood scores in final game of Leeds United's season to secure golden boot |website=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]] |date=8 May 2017 |access-date=24 May 2017}}</ref>

Wood won the [[EFL Championship Player of the Month]] award for January 2017,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.efl.com/news/article/2016/chris-wood-named-sky-bet-championship-player-of-the-month-3566725.aspx |title=Chris Wood named Sky Bet Championship Player of the Month |publisher=English Football League |date=10 February 2017 |access-date=24 May 2017}}</ref> and was voted PFA Fans' Championship Player of the Month for both January and March.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thepfa.com/thepfa/pfa-fans-player-of-the-month/potm-winners-16-17 |title=2016/17 winners |publisher=Professional Footballers' Association |access-date=24 May 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170812215054/https://www.thepfa.com/thepfa/pfa-fans-player-of-the-month/potm-winners-16-17 |archive-date=12 August 2017 |url-status=dead}}</ref> He was shortlisted for Championship Player of the Season, but lost out to Brighton's [[Anthony Knockaert]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/39548007 |title=Brighton's Anthony Knockaert is named Championship Player of the Year |website=BBC Sport |date=9 April 2017 |access-date=24 May 2017}}</ref> Wood and teammate [[Pontus Jansson]] were named in the EFL Championship Team of the Season and the EFL (all divisions) Team of the Season,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/10807996/efl-teams-of-the-season-announced-for-the-sky-bet-championship-league-one-and-league-two |title=EFL teams of the season announced for the Sky Bet Championship, League One and League Two |website=Sky Sports |date=20 March 2017 |access-date=24 May 2017}}<br />{{cite news |url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11689/10832016/efl-team-of-the-season-chris-wood-anthony-knockaert-and-billy-sharp-included |title=EFL team of the season: Chris Wood, Anthony Knockaert and Billy Sharp included |website=Sky Sports |date=11 March 2017 |access-date=24 May 2017}}</ref> and Wood was the only Leeds player selected for the [[PFA Team of the Year (2010s)#2016–17|PFA Championship Team of the Year]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/football/leeds-united/only-one-leeds-united-player-named-in-pfa-championship-team-of-the-year-1-8502363 |title=Only one Leeds United player named in PFA Championship Team of the Year |first=Lee |last=Sobot |newspaper=Yorkshire Evening Post |location=Leeds |date=20 April 2017 |access-date=24 May 2017}}</ref> At club level, he won Leeds United's Player of the Year and Players' Player of the Year awards for 2016–17.<ref name="Press1617"/>

On 6 August 2017, Wood scored his first goal of the season in the 3–2 victory against [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.leedsunited.com/news/team-news/22152/report-bolton-wanderers-2-3-leeds-united |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170807021105/https://www.leedsunited.com/news/team-news/22152/report-bolton-wanderers-2-3-leeds-united |url-status=dead |archive-date=7 August 2017 |title=Report: Bolton Wanderers 2–3 Leeds United |publisher=Leeds United F.C. |date=6 August 2017 |access-date=19 February 2018}}</ref> On 18 August, after the club had rejected a £12&nbsp;million offer from Premier League club Burnley earlier in the week, Leeds offered Wood a new three-year contract in an attempt to keep him at the club.<ref name=WoodGoing>{{cite news |url=http://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/football/leeds-united/wood-s-leeds-united-future-in-fresh-doubt-as-burnley-fight-to-close-out-deal-1-8711356 |title=Wood's Leeds United future in fresh doubt as Burnley fight to close out deal |first=Phil |last=Hay |newspaper=Yorkshire Evening Post |location=Leeds |date=19 August 2017 |access-date=21 August 2017}}</ref> In the expectation of a further, successful, bid, he ruled himself out of the match against [[Sunderland A.F.C|Sunderland]] on 19 August.<ref name=WoodGoing/>

===Burnley===
On 21 August 2017, Wood signed a four-year contract with Premier League club [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] for an undisclosed club-record fee,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.burnleyfootballclub.com/news/2017/august/clarets-make-wood-record-buy/ |title=Clarets make Wood record buy |publisher=Burnley F.C. |date=21 August 2017 |access-date=21 August 2017 |archive-date=21 August 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170821212546/https://www.burnleyfootballclub.com/news/2017/august/clarets-make-wood-record-buy/ |url-status=dead}}</ref> widely reported as £15&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/41001685 |title=Chris Wood: Burnley sign Leeds United striker for club record fee |website=BBC Sport |date=21 August 2017 |access-date=21 August 2017}}<br />{{cite news |url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11708/10999187/burnley-sign-leeds-uniteds-chris-wood-on-four-year-deal |title=Burnley sign Leeds United's Chris Wood on four-year deal |first=Andy |last=Charles |website=Sky Sports |date=21 August 2017 |access-date=21 August 2017}}</ref> Wood made his Burnley debut on 27 August against [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] at [[Wembley Stadium]] in the Premier League, and scored an equaliser in the second minute of stoppage time in a match which finished 1–1.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40990430 |title=Tottenham Hotspur 1–1 Burnley |first=Timothy |last=Abraham |website=BBC Sport |date=27 August 2017 |access-date=19 February 2018}}</ref>

On 19 September, in the [[EFL Cup]] third round, Wood scored against his former club Leeds United at [[Turf Moor]] in the 89th minute from the penalty spot. The match ended 2–2 after [[extra time]], and Leeds won the match 5–3 on penalties.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.skysports.com/football/burnley-vs-leeds/384188 |title=Burnley 2–2 Leeds (AET): Championship side win 5–3 on penalties |website=Sky Sports |date=29 September 2017 |access-date=19 February 2018}}</ref> On 8 November 2019, Wood signed a new contract committing himself to Burnley until 2023.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/50352478 |title=Chris Wood: Burnley striker signs new contract to 2023 |website=BBC Sport |date=8 November 2019|access-date=9 November 2019}}</ref>

Wood scored in the final match of the [[2019–20 Premier League|2019–20]] season in Burnley's 2–1 defeat to Brighton on 26 July 2020.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/53460585 |title=Brighton recorded their highest Premier League points total as they completed their campaign with an impressive win at Burnley. |website=BBC Sport |date=26 July 2020|access-date=26 July 2020}}</ref> It was his 14th goal of the season, both his highest return in the Premier League and best scoring season overall in a Burnley shirt.{{citation needed|date=February 2023}}

On 6 March 2021, Wood scored his 40th goal in the Premier League in a 1–1 draw against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]], as well as becoming the eighth player in the history of the club to start 100 Premier League games for Burnley.<ref>{{cite news |title=Xhaka error gifts Burnley point |website=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/56220041|access-date=6 March 2021}}</ref> On 25 April, he scored his first hat-trick for Burnley in a 4–0 away league win against [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]], becoming the first New Zealander to score three goals in a Premier League match.<ref>{{cite news |last=Rostance |first=Tom |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/56790343 |title=Wolverhampton Wanderers 0–4 Burnley |website=BBC Sport |date=25 April 2021|access-date=25 April 2021}}</ref>

===Newcastle United===
On 13 January 2022, Wood signed a two-and-a-half-year contract with [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] for a fee reported to be £25&nbsp;million, after his release clause was triggered.<ref>{{cite news |date=13 January 2022 |title=Newcastle transfer news: Chris Wood signs from Burnley in £25m deal to become second January arrival |website=Sky Sports |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11678/12514215/newcastle-transfer-news-chris-wood-signs-from-burnley-in-25m-deal-to-become-second-january-arrival |access-date=13 January 2022}}</ref> Newcastle manager [[Eddie Howe]] said that Wood was an important signing at a crucial time of the season.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Newcastle United sign Chris Wood from Burnley |url=https://www.nufc.co.uk/news/latest-news/newcastle-united-sign-chris-wood-from-burnley/ |publisher=Newcastle United F.C. |date=13 January 2022 |access-date=13 January 2022}}</ref> Wood himself saw the move as an "exciting opportunity" after becoming the club's second signing since the takeover from a [[Public Investment Fund|Saudi]]-backed consortium.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Newcastle takeover completed: Saudi-led consortium end Mike Ashley's 14-year ownership |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11678/12427983/newcastle-takeover-completed-saudi-led-consortium-end-mike-ashleys-14-year-ownership |website=Sky Sports |date=8 October 2021 |access-date=13 January 2022}}</ref> He made his Newcastle debut two days after signing when he started in a 1–1 draw against Watford,<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/59918928 |title=Newcastle United 1–1 Watford |first=Alistair |last=Magowan |website=BBC Sport |date=15 January 2022 |access-date=21 February 2023}}</ref> and his first goal for the club was the equaliser in a 2–1 league win over Southampton on 10 March.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/southampton-newcastle-player-ratings-bruno-23348051 |title=Southampton 1–2 Newcastle player ratings as Bruno Guimaraes among three 10s on the South Coast |first=Lee |last=Ryder |newspaper=Evening Chronicle |location=Newcastle upon Tyne |date=10 March 2022 |access-date=21 February 2023}}</ref>

===Nottingham Forest===
Wood found his first-team chances at Newcastle limited, and on 20 January 2023, he joined Premier League club [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] on loan to the end of the season. The deal included an obligation to buy should certain conditions be met.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Newcastle United agree loan deal with Nottingham Forest for Chris Wood |url=https://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/sport/23263215.newcastle-united-agree-loan-deal-nottingham-forest-chris-wood/ |first=Scott |last=Wilson |newspaper=The Northern Echo |location=Darlington |date=19 January 2023 |access-date=21 February 2023}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nottinghamforest.co.uk/news/2023/january/20/forest-complete-signing-of-chris-wood/ |title=Forest complete signing of Chris Wood |publisher=Nottingham Forest F.C. |date=20 January 2023 |access-date=21 February 2023}}</ref> His first goal, an 84th-minute tap-in, earned Forest a draw at home to [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] on 18 February.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/64607249 |title=Nottingham Forest 1–1 Manchester City |first=Jess |last=Anderson |website=BBC Sport |date=18 February 2023 |access-date=21 February 2023}}</ref> On 30 March 2023, the club announced Wood would miss the rest of the season with a thigh injury.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Nottingham Forest face injury blow as striker Chris Wood is ruled out for remainder of the season |url=https://ca.sports.yahoo.com/news/nottingham-forest-face-injury-blow-124600248.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230330195753/https://ca.sports.yahoo.com/news/nottingham-forest-face-injury-blow-124600248.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=30 March 2023 |access-date=30 March 2023 |website=Yahoo Sports |date=30 March 2023 }}</ref>

In June 2023, his transfer to Nottingham Forest became permanent,<ref>{{cite news |title=Forest Confirm Retained List |url=https://www.nottinghamforest.co.uk/news/2023/june/02/forest-confirm-retained-list/ |access-date=2 June 2023 |publisher=Nottingham Forest F.C. |date=2 June 2023}}</ref> for a reported fee of £15&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite web |last=Taylor |first=Paul |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/4219262/2023/02/17/chris-wood-nottingham-forest-transfer/ |title=Chris Wood's move to Nottingham Forest made permanent |publisher=The Athletic |date=17 February 2023 }}</ref> Later that year, on 26 December, he scored a hat-trick in a 3–1 away victory over Newcastle United,<ref>{{cite web |last=Mendola |first=Nicholas |url=https://www.nbcsports.com/soccer/news/newcastle-vs-nottingham-forest-how-to-watch-live-stream-link-team-news |title=Chris Wood hat trick leads Nottingham Forest to superb win at Newcastle |publisher=NBC Sports |date=26 December 2023 }}</ref> becoming only the fourth player in Premier League history to achieve this feat against his former club following [[Andy Cole]], [[Marcus Bent]] and [[Joshua King (footballer, born 1992)|Joshua King]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Smyth |first=Aaron |url=https://www.givemesport.com/the-players-to-score-a-premier-league-hat-trick-against-former-club/ |title=The players to score a Premier League hat-trick against former club |publisher=GiveMeSport |date=26 December 2023 }}</ref> In the 2023–24 season, Wood was Nottingham Forest's top goalscorer, with 15 goals in 35 appearances across all competitions.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Nottingham Forest 2023–24 Top Scorers – Football |url=https://www.sportsmole.co.uk/football/nottingham-forest/2023-24/top-scorers.html |access-date=22 October 2024 |website=Sports Mole}}</ref>

Wood was named the [[Premier League Player of the Month]] for October 2024, as the league's top scorer for the month with four goals in his three appearances. He became the first Nottingham Forest player and first New Zealander to win the award.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/4164752 |title=Wood makes history with EA Sports Player of the Month award |date=8 November 2024 |publisher=Premier League |access-date=10 November 2024}}</ref> On 7 December 2024, he became Forest's top leading goalscorer in the Premier League, bypassing [[Bryan Roy]], as he netted the winner in a 3–2 away victory over [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]. The goal was Wood's 25th for the club, and secured Forest's first win at [[Old Trafford]] since a 2–1 triumph on 17 December 1994.<ref>{{Cite web |date=7 December 2024 |title=Wood sets Forest record to hand Amorim his first home defeat |url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/4190015 |access-date=7 December 2024 |publisher=Premier League}}</ref>

In January 2025, Wood signed a new deal with the club, extending his contract to 2027.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Jackson |first=Bobbie |date=23 January 2025 |title=Chris Wood: Nottingham Forest striker signs extension until 2027 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/cd64gq5lvpxo |access-date=23 January 2025 |website=BBC Sport |language=en}}</ref> On 1 February, he netted a hat-trick, the third goal of which was a penalty, in a 7–0 victory over Brighton, becoming the first Nottingham Forest player to achieve this feat at the [[City Ground]] in the top flight since [[Nigel Clough]] in December 1987.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.beinsports.com/en-us/soccer/premier-league/articles/hat-trick-hero-wood-lauds-forests-character-after-brighton-thrashing-2025-02-01 |title=Hat-trick hero Wood lauds Forest's character after Brighton thrashing |publisher=beIN SPORTS |date=1 February 2025 |access-date=2 February 2025}}</ref> Wood scored his 20th goal of the season on 11 May during a 2–2 draw against his former club Leicester City, which secured Forest's qualification for European competitions for the first time in 30 years.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/football/english-premier-league/chris-wood-scores-20th-goal-of-season-nottingham-forest-denied-by-leicester/63E4ECWUUBAGTMOGAM2SJGONAU/ |title=Chris Wood scores 20th goal of season, Nottingham Forest denied by Leicester |newspaper=The New Zealand Herald |agency=Agence France-Presse |date=11 May 2025 |access-date=21 May 2025}}</ref> In addition, he became the second Forest player to reach 20 Premier League goals in one season, following [[Stan Collymore]] in 1994–95.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.beinsports.com/en-us/soccer/premier-league/articles/nottingham-forest-2-2-leicester-city-hosts-seal-european-spot-but-miss-chance-to-reclaim-fifth-2025-05-11 |title=Nottingham Forest 2-2 Leicester City: Hosts seal European spot but miss chance to reclaim fifth |publisher=beIN SPORTS USA |date=11 May 2025 }}</ref> At the end of the [[2024–25 Premier League|2024–25 season]], Wood was voted into the [[PFA Team of the Year]] by his fellow Premier League players.<ref>{{Cite web |date=19 August 2025 |title=PFA Premier League Team of the Year |url=https://www.thepfa.com/news/2025/8/19/pfa-pl-toty-2025 |access-date=5 September 2025 |website=Professional Footballers' Association}}</ref> In October 2025, it was reported that Wood had sustained a knee injury that would see him out of action until March 2026, with surgery later performed in December 2025.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Taylor |first=Paul |date=27 December 2025 |title=Chris Wood will be back for Nottingham Forest within 'weeks' of surgery, Sean Dyche hopes |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/6921286/2025/12/27/chris-wood-nottingham-forest-surgery-update/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/ |archive-date=4 January 2026 |website=The Athletic}}</ref> On 9 April 2026, Wood returned to action, starting in a 1–1 away draw with [[FC Porto|Porto]] in the [[2025–26 UEFA Europa League knockout phase|Europa League quarter-final]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Mashiter |first=Nick |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/c04xr2znkpkt |title=Porto 1–1 Nottingham Forest |publisher=BBC Sport |date=9 April 2026 }}</ref>

==International career==
[[File:2017 Confederation Cup - MEXNZL - Chris Wood.jpg|thumb|upright|Wood playing for [[New Zealand men's national football team|New Zealand]] at the [[2017 FIFA Confederations Cup]]]]

Wood represented New Zealand at [[New Zealand national under-17 football team|under-17]] level and was a standout performer for the All Whites at the [[2007 FIFA U-17 World Cup]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Chris Wood, the All White hope |url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/news/y=2010/m=5/news=chris-wood-the-all-white-hope-1210963.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180305063527/http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/news/y=2010/m=5/news=chris-wood-the-all-white-hope-1210963.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=5 March 2018 |publisher=FIFA |access-date=4 March 2018 |date=14 May 2010}}</ref> a tournament which earned him a trial with West Brom, for whom he later signed.<ref name="birminghammail"/>

After a string of impressive performances at club level, Wood's rise on the international stage continued as he was fast-tracked into All Whites coach [[Ricki Herbert]]'s squad for the [[2009 FIFA Confederations Cup]] in South Africa.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/confederationscup/news/y=2009/m=5/news=kiwis-call-teen-for-south-africa-1055303.html |title=Kiwis call up teen for South Africa |agency=Agence France-Presse |publisher=FIFA |date=7 May 2009 |access-date=19 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151120002834/https://www.fifa.com/confederationscup/news/y=2009/m=5/news=kiwis-call-teen-for-south-africa-1055303.html|archive-date=20 November 2015}}</ref> He made his debut in a [[Friendly (association football)|friendly]] against [[Tanzania national football team|Tanzania]] on 3 June 2009 in a warm-up match for the tournament.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/confederationscup/news/y=2009/m=6/news=kiwis-taste-defeat-africa-1066153.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151120001421/http://www.fifa.com/confederationscup/news/y=2009/m=6/news=kiwis-taste-defeat-africa-1066153.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=20 November 2015 |title=Kiwis taste defeat in Africa |publisher=FIFA |date=3 June 2009 |access-date=19 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/confederationscup/archive/southafrica2009/teams/team=43978/players.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151120003021/http://www.fifa.com/confederationscup/archive/southafrica2009/teams/team=43978/players.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=20 November 2015 |title=FIFA Confederations Cup South Africa 2009: Teams: New Zealand Squad List |publisher=FIFA |access-date=19 November 2015}}</ref>

In May 2010, Wood was named in the All Whites World Cup squad for the [[2010 FIFA World Cup]], and at 18 was the youngest member of the New Zealand team which travelled to South Africa.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/3676399/All-Whites-World-Cup-squad-named |title=All Whites World Cup squad named |website=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]] |first=Duncan |last=Johnstone |date=9 October 2010 |url-status=dead |access-date=11 May 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180305064802/https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/3676399/All-Whites-World-Cup-squad-named |archive-date=5 March 2018}}</ref> He came on as a substitute in the first group match in a 1–1 draw against [[Slovakia national football team|Slovakia]] as New Zealand claimed their first ever point in a World Cup finals match.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/world_cup_2010/matches/match_12/default.stm |title=New Zealand 1–1 Slovakia |website=BBC Sport |date=15 June 2010 |access-date=19 November 2015}}</ref> He appeared as a substitute in New Zealand's remaining group matches, a 1–1 draw with defending champions [[Italy national football team|Italy]] and a 0–0 draw with [[Paraguay national football team|Paraguay]],<ref>{{cite news |last=Wyatt |first=Chris |title=Italy 1–1 New Zealand |url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/world_cup_2010/matches/match_28/default.stm|access-date=5 March 2018 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref> as they were knocked out of the tournament after drawing all three group games.<ref>{{cite news |last=Chowdhury |first=Saj |title=Paraguay 0–0 New Zealand |url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/world_cup_2010/matches/match_42/default.stm|access-date=5 March 2018 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref>

Wood scored his first international goal on 10 October 2010 in his country's 1–1 draw with [[Honduras national football team|Honduras]]. He was given a yellow card for the unusual nature of his celebration of the goal, where he revealed his underwear to the spectators.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nzfootball.co.nz/woodzee-nets-as-all-whites-thrill/ |title=Woodzee nets as All Whites thrill |publisher=New Zealand Football |date=9 October 2010 |access-date=19 November 2015 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151120004950/http://www.nzfootball.co.nz/woodzee-nets-as-all-whites-thrill/ |archive-date=20 November 2015}}</ref>

Wood scored his first international hat-trick against [[Solomon Islands national football team|Solomon Islands]] on 10 June 2012 in the third place play-off of the OFC Nations Cup.<ref>{{cite web |title=Chris Wood hat-trick helps the All Whites move one step closer to the World Cup |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/nz-teams/96387863/chris-wood-hattrick-helps-the-all-whites-move-one-step-closer-to-the-world-cup |website=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]] |first=Andrew |last=Voerman |date=1 September 2017|access-date=26 February 2018}}</ref> He was named in the [[New Zealand national under-23 football team|New Zealand under-23]] squad for the [[Football at the 2012 Summer Olympics|2012 Olympics]], and scored in a 1–1 draw against [[Egypt national under-23 football team|Egypt under-23s]] on 29 July 2012 at [[Old Trafford]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Egypt 1 New Zealand 1 |url=http://www.skysports.com/football/egypt-vs-new-zealand/271334|access-date=5 March 2018 |website=Sky Sports |date=29 July 2012}}</ref> He also started the final group game in a 3–0 defeat to [[Brazil national under-23 football team|Brazil under-23]]s which saw the New Zealand Olympic squad knocked out of the tournament.<ref>{{cite news |title=Brazil 3 New Zealand 0 |url=http://www.skysports.com/football/brazil-vs-new-zealand/271397|access-date=5 March 2018 |website=Sky Sports}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Di Maggio |first=Roberto |title=Games of the XXX. Olympiad |url=https://www.rsssf.org/tableso/ol2012f.html |publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation |access-date=5 March 2018}}</ref>

On 14 November 2014, Wood became the youngest ever captain for the All Whites, a record previously held by [[Tommy Smith (footballer, born 1990)|Tommy Smith]].<ref name="Wood Youngest Captain">{{cite news |url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/news/article.cfm?c_id=4&objectid=11358199 |title=Wood youngest captain |first=Steven |last=Holloway |newspaper=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |location=Auckland |date=14 November 2014 |access-date=1 June 2016}}</ref>

He scored four goals in the [[2016 OFC Nations Cup]] for New Zealand, helping them win the tournament and to qualify for the Confederations Cup.<ref name=Soccerway>{{cite web |url=https://int.soccerway.com/players/chris-wood/76918/ |title=C. Wood: Summary |website=Soccerway |publisher=Perform Group |access-date=28 January 2022 |archive-date=28 August 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230828103542/https://int.soccerway.com/players/chris-wood/76918/ |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=FIFA>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/confederationscup/news/y=2016/m=6/news=new-zealand-regain-crown-amid-broadening-pyramid-2801358.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160616035110/http://www.fifa.com/confederationscup/news/y=2016/m=6/news=new-zealand-regain-crown-amid-broadening-pyramid-2801358.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=16 June 2016 |title=New Zealand regain crown amid broadening pyramid |publisher=FIFA |date=13 June 2016 |access-date=13 June 2016}}</ref>

With Wood being his country's [[Vice-captain (association football)|vice-captain]], in the absence of captain [[Winston Reid]], he captained his country twice during November 2016, both against [[New Caledonia national football team|New Caledonia]], first in a 3–0 victory on 12 November, and then in a 0–0 draw three days later.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.leedsunited.com/news/team-news/21344/international-november-round-up-part-2 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161118163025/https://www.leedsunited.com/news/team-news/21344/international-november-round-up-part-2 |url-status=dead |archive-date=18 November 2016 |title=International: November round-up part 2 |publisher=Leeds United F.C. |date=16 November 2016 |access-date=16 November 2016}}</ref> After being selected as captain for the [[2017 FIFA Confederations Cup]], Wood scored his only goal of the tournament on 21 June in a 2–1 defeat against [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/news/video-leeds-united-striker-chris-wood-scores-for-new-zealand-against-mexico-1-8609031 |title=Leeds United striker Chris Wood scores for New Zealand against Mexico |first=Alex |last=Evans |newspaper=Yorkshire Evening Post |location=Leeds |date=21 June 2017 |access-date=19 February 2018}}</ref>

Wood was named as one of the three [[List of overage players in Olympic football|overage players]] to participate in the [[Football at the 2020 Summer Olympics|2020 Summer Olympics]] in Tokyo, Japan.<ref>{{Cite web |date=22 July 2021 |title=Sore losers: South Korea's rude snub to Kiwi football star |url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/olympics/tokyo-olympics-2020-football-south-korean-player-lee-dong-gyeong-snubs-chris-wood-after-oly-whites-win/PLNBOSKQRIAU2VU62LWSJSCMHY/ |access-date=2025-01-03 |website=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |language=en-NZ}}</ref>

In March 2022, after scoring twice during [[New Zealand men's national football team|New Zealand]]'s 4–0 win over [[Fiji national football team|Fiji]] at the [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification|2022 FIFA World Cup qualifiers]] in Qatar, Wood became the men's leading goal scorer with 30 goals, overtaking the previous record of 29, held by [[Vaughan Coveny]] since 25 May 2006.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rollo |first1=Phillip |title=Chris Wood becomes All Whites' all-time leading scorer with brace against Fiji |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/nz-teams/128124188/chris-wood-becomes-all-whites-alltime-leading-scorer-with-brace-against-fiji |website=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]] |access-date=21 March 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Burgess |first1=Michael |title=Football: Chris Wood makes history as All Whites dominate Fiji |url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/football-chris-wood-makes-history-as-all-whites-dominate-fiji/D42MIAVFEJZ45QYAVRXGXOMHIA/ |access-date=21 March 2022 |newspaper=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |location=Auckland}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Rollo |first1=Phillip |title='It means a lot': Chris Wood creates history with 30th goal for All Whites |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/nz-teams/128124191/it-means-a-lot-chris-wood-creates-history-with-30th-goal-for-all-whites |website=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]] |date=22 March 2022}}</ref>

On 14 May 2026, Wood was named in the 26-man squad for the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nzfootball.co.nz/newsarticle/165753?newsfeedId=1841052 |title=New Zealand Squad Named for FIFA World Cup 2026 |publisher=[[New Zealand Football]] |date=May 14, 2026 |access-date=May 14, 2026 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20260514122914/https://www.nzfootball.co.nz/newsarticle/165753 |archive-date=May 14, 2026}}</ref> A month later, on 2 June, he earned his 89th international cap in a 4–0 friendly defeat to [[Haiti national football team|Haiti]], becoming his country's all-time appearance record holder, surpassing previous record of [[Ivan Vicelich]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.goal.com/en/lists/nottingham-forest-chris-wood-history-new-zealand-world-cup-scotland-haiti/bltabd2128a8fe126b0 |title=Nottingham Forest striker Chris Wood makes history with New Zealand as World Cup minnows embarrassingly thrashed by Scotland's opponents Haiti |publisher=Goal.com |date=3 June 2026 }}</ref>

